        <definition>
        <title>Cross Product (Algebraic Definition)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>cross product</term><idx><h>cross product</h></idx> <m>\vu \times \vv</m> of vectors <m>\vu = u_1\vi + u_2\vj + u_3\vk</m> and <m>\vv = v_1\vi + v_2\vj + v_3\vk</m> in <m>\R^3</m> is the vector 
          <men xml:id="E_9_4_cross_def">
            (u_2v_3-u_3v_2)\vi - (u_1v_3-u_3v_1)\vj + (u_1v_2-u_2v_1)\vk.
          </men>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <remark>
      <p>
          The cross product formula looks complicated, but it can be easily remembered as the result
          of computing the determinant of a 3x3 matrix.
      </p>
      <me>
        \vu\times\vv = 
        \left|
          \begin{array}{ccc}
            \vi \amp  \vj \amp  \vk \\
            u_1 \amp  u_2 \amp  u_3 \\
            v_1 \amp  v_2 \amp  v_3
        \end{array} 
        \right|.
      </me>
      <p>
        Keep in mind that this is a mnemonic device. This is not really a matrix like the ones you know
        from linear algebra beacuse it has some entries that are scalars and others that are vectors. However,
        the formula is not unrelated to linear algebra because you can derive it by solving a system of 
        equations using row reduction.
      </p>
    </remark>

